arguments.prompt:
I need to understand the APIs available in these NuGet packages for a .NET 10 AI agent console app:

1. `Microsoft.Extensions.AI` (v10.5.0) - The core AI abstractions
2. `Microsoft.Extensions.AI.Abstractions` (v10.5.0) - Abstractions for AI
3. `Microsoft.Agents.AI` (v1.3.0) - Agent framework

The DLLs are at:
- /home/runner/.nuget/packages/microsoft.extensions.ai/10.5.0/lib/net9.0/Microsoft.Extensions.AI.dll
- /home/runner/.nuget/packages/microsoft.extensions.ai.abstractions/10.5.0/lib/net9.0/Microsoft.Extensions.AI.Abstractions.dll
- /home/runner/.nuget/packages/microsoft.agents.ai/1.3.0/lib/net9.0/Microsoft.Agents.AI.dll
- /home/runner/.nuget/packages/microsoft.extensions.ai.openai/9.5.0/lib/net8.0/Microsoft.Extensions.AI.OpenAI.dll (check this path or find it)

Also check the OpenAI package:
- Find the OpenAI DLL under ~/.nuget/packages/openai/

For each DLL, run:
```
dotnet tool list -g 2>/dev/null  # check if ilspy is available
```

Use this approach to list public types:
```bash
python3 -c "
import subprocess, re
result = subprocess.run(['dotnet', '/home/runner/.nuget/packages/ilspycmd/9.0.0.7894/tools/net8.0/any/ilspycmd.dll', '<DLL_PATH>'], capture_output=True, text=True)
print(result.stdout[:5000])
"
```

Actually, first find if ilspycmd is available:
```bash
find ~/.nuget -name "ilspycmd.dll" 2>/dev/null
```

If not, just use `python3` with a simpler approach - list all public types using reflection via a quick C# script:

Create and run a .NET script that loads each assembly and lists public types and their public methods. Use something like:

```bash
cat > /tmp/inspect.csx << 'EOF'
using System.Reflection;
var path = args[0];
var asm = Assembly.LoadFrom(path);
foreach (var t in asm.GetExportedTypes().OrderBy(t => t.FullName))
{
    Console.WriteLine($"\n=== {t.FullName} ===");
    if (t.BaseType != null && t.BaseType != typeof(object))
        Console.WriteLine($"  Base: {t.BaseType.FullName}");
    foreach (var iface in t.GetInterfaces().Where(i => i.IsPublic))
        Console.WriteLine($"  Implements: {iface.Name}");
    foreach (var m in t.GetMethods(BindingFlags.Public | BindingFlags.Instance | BindingFlags.Static | BindingFlags.DeclaredOnly))
    {
        var parms = string.Join(", ", m.GetParameters().Select(p => $"{p.ParameterType.Name} {p.Name}"));
        Console.WriteLine($"  {m.ReturnType.Name} {m.Name}({parms})");
    }
    foreach (var p in t.GetProperties(BindingFlags.Public | BindingFlags.Instance | BindingFlags.DeclaredOnly))
        Console.WriteLine($"  prop {p.PropertyType.Name} {p.Name}");
}
EOF
```

Actually, the simplest approach - create a temporary C# console app that inspects:

```bash
mkdir -p /tmp/inspect && cd /tmp/inspect
cat > Program.cs << 'CEOF'
using System.Reflection;

string[] dlls = [
    "/home/runner/.nuget/packages/microsoft.extensions.ai.abstractions/10.5.0/lib/net9.0/Microsoft.Extensions.AI.Abstractions.dll",
    "/home/runner/.nuget/packages/microsoft.extensions.ai/10.5.0/lib/net9.0/Microsoft.Extensions.AI.dll",
    "/home/runner/.nuget/packages/microsoft.agents.ai/1.3.0/lib/net9.0/Microsoft.Agents.AI.dll"
];

foreach (var path in dlls)
{
    Console.WriteLine($"\n\n========== {Path.GetFileName(path)} ==========");
    try
    {
        var asm = Assembly.LoadFrom(path);
        foreach (var t in asm.GetExportedTypes().OrderBy(t => t.FullName))
        {
            Console.WriteLine($"\n--- {t.FullName} ---");
            if (t.BaseType != null && t.BaseType != typeof(object))
                Console.WriteLine($"  Base: {t.BaseType}");
            foreach (var iface in t.GetInterfaces().Where(i => i.IsPublic).Take(5))
                Console.WriteLine($"  Impl: {iface.Name}");
            foreach (var c in t.GetConstructors(BindingFlags.Public | BindingFlags.Instance))
            {
                var cp = string.Join(", ", c.GetParameters().Select(p => $"{p.ParameterType.Name} {p.Name}"));
                Console.WriteLine($"  ctor({cp})");
            }
            foreach (var m in t.GetMethods(BindingFlags.Public | BindingFlags.Instance | BindingFlags.Static | BindingFlags.DeclaredOnly).Take(20))
            {
                var parms = string.Join(", ", m.GetParameters().Select(p => $"{p.ParameterType.Name} {p.Name}"));
                Console.WriteLine($"  {m.ReturnType.Name} {m.Name}({parms})");
            }
            foreach (var p in t.GetProperties(BindingFlags.Public | BindingFlags.Instance | BindingFlags.DeclaredOnly))
                Console.WriteLine($"  prop {p.PropertyType.Name} {p.Name}");
        }
    }
    catch (Exception ex)
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"  ERROR: {ex.Message}");
    }
}
CEOF

cat > inspect.csproj << 'PEOF'
<Project Sdk="Microsoft.NET.Sdk">
  <PropertyGroup>
    <TargetFramework>net10.0</TargetFramework>
    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>
  </PropertyGroup>
</Project>
PEOF

dotnet run 2>&1
```

Report ALL the output, especially:
1. What types exist in Microsoft.Extensions.AI related to tool calling / function calling
2. What types exist in Microsoft.Agents.AI for building agents
3. What is AIFunction, AITool, ChatOptions, etc.
4. How FunctionInvokingChatClient or similar works

Also look for any XML docs:
```bash
find ~/.nuget/packages/microsoft.extensions.ai/10.5.0 -name "*.xml" | head -5
cat $(find ~/.nuget/packages/microsoft.extensions.ai/10.5.0 -name "*.xml" -path "*/net9.0/*" | head -1) | head -200
```

And:
```bash
find ~/.nuget/packages/microsoft.agents.ai/1.3.0 -name "*.xml" | head -5
cat $(find ~/.nuget/packages/microsoft.agents.ai/1.3.0 -name "*.xml" -path "*/net9.0/*" | head -1) | head -300
```

Also find the OpenAI extension DLL:
```bash
find ~/.nuget/packages/microsoft.extensions.ai.openai -name "*.dll" 2>/dev/null
```

